		Comment <a href="#c_1713726171">9</a> by Tom Link
		posted on 9/4/2010 at 12:18 AM
		</div>
		<div class="comment_text"><p>Glad you found SpatialKey useful, Ray.  I don't know if you've found this yet, but SpatialKey could produce all of the charts you posted earlier - breakdown by time of day, day of week, crime type - and allow you to filter by any of those elements.  So, you could see what types of crimes happen on Monday afternoons, or where the Explosions occurred, or when crimes happen in a particular area, etc.</p><p>One thing to note is that location data can often deceive.  For example, often our police departments will see hotspots at the police station, because a location is not provided and that's the default location.  Or, the only location provided is a zip code, and you end up with a false hotspot that is the centerpoint of that zipcode.  (SpatialKey actually has a way to filter out data that it knows is less precise or incorrect.)<br>The good news is that visualizing and reporting data like this often exposes quality issues and helps to correct them.</p><p>@alan - a "bad area" of town or just a more populated one :)  It gets interesting when you correlate this with demographics or even changes in the same place over time.</p></div>
	</div>
